High Earners Using Public Transporation¶

Molly Wilson¶

Public transportation is extremely useful for commuters, especially those with a lower income who cannot afford to drive. I've been really aware of the lack of public transportation in the united states since I visited Amsterdam. Amsterdam is a beautiful city where everything is accessable by walking, biking, or public transportation. Cars on the roads are few and far between. It is so different from the United States, where only cities have any sort of public transportation, and it leaves a lot to be desired. This is what ultimately pushed me to do research on public transportation data in the United States. After finding and analyzing some data about public transportation usage in the United States, I found an interesting trend in the public transportation usage among higher earners. After discovering this trend, I decided to attempt to create a linear model that would best predict the number of high earners who used public transportation based on a number of factors that I will explain below.

The Walkability Dataset¶

The in this dataset, the walkability index for each block is calculated by using the formula $$(\dfrac{w}{3}) + (\dfrac{x}{3}) + (\dfrac{y}{6}) + (\dfrac{z}{6})$$

where
$w =$ block group's ranked score for intersection density
$x =$ block group's ranked score for proximity to transit stops
$y =$ block group's ranked score for employment mix
$z =$ block group's ranked score for employment and household mix

The National Walkability Index: Methodology and User Guide contains more information on the way that walkability data can be used and interpreted. You can also access the full dataset here.

In [47]:
walkability_df = pd.read_csv('downloads/EPA_SmartLocationDatabase_V3_Jan_2021_Final.csv')

Access to Jobs and Workers via Transit Dataset¶

The boundaries for blocks are derived from the US Census 2010. Click here for more information about the dataset.

Useful Features:¶

TrAccess_Index: An index of relative accessiblity compared to other blocks within the same metro region
Pop_byTr: Total population able to access the block group within 45-minute transit and walking commute
Pop_byTr_av: The weighted average Pop_byTr among all block groups within the same CBSA
Pct_Pop_byTr: Total population able to access the block group within a 45-minute transit and walking commute as a percentage of total regional population
HU_byTr: total housing units reachable within a 45 minute transit and walking commute
HH_byTr: Households able to access the block group within a 45-minute transit and walking commute
Wrks_byTr: Employed population able to access the block group within a 45-minute transit commute from their home location
Pct_Wrks_byTr: Employed population able to access the block group within a 45-minute transit commute from their home location as a percentage of total regional employed population
LoWgWrks_byTr: Number of low wage workersthat can reach the block group within a 45 minute transit commute
MeWgWrks_byTr: Number of medium-wage workers that can reach the block group within a 45 minute transit commute
HiWgWrks_byTr: Number of high-wage workers that can reach the block group within a 45-minute transit commute
Jobs_byTr: Total jobs reachable within a 45-minute transit and walking commute
Pct_Jobs_byTr: Total jobs reachable within a 45-minute transit and walking commute as a percentage of total regional jobs

In [157]:
# I am going to write a function that will normalize the feature of the dataframe that I give it
def normalize(df, feature):
    lst = list(df[feature])
    sorted_lst = sorted(list(df[~pd.isnull(df[feature])][feature]))
    mini = sorted_lst[0]
    maxi = sorted_lst[len(sorted_lst) - 1]
    ran = maxi - mini
    for i in range(len(lst)):
        #if lst[i] != np.nan:
        lst[i] = (lst[i] - mini)/ran
    df[feature + '_norm'] = lst

Data Analysis¶

As I mentioned before the split in the model for high wage workers is really interesting, so I'm going to create a linear regression model with multiple variables to figure out what the best predictors for this model are and find a linear equation that best predicts the norm of the number of high wage workers with access to their jobs via public transportation.

First, I'm going to split my data into a training data set of the first 20,000 and the rest will be the test set so that I can train my model and then use the test data to help me minimize loss. Since I cut out all of the NaN entries in the lists, the lengths of the final training and test sets are varying.

# function that predicts the HiWgWrks_byTr_norm value
def Hi_Wg_Predict(theta, jobs=0, low=0, pop=0, access=0, med=0):
    return theta[0] + jobs * theta[1] + low * theta[2] + pop * theta[3] + access * theta[4] + med * theta[5]

    sq_loss = ((y_hat - y) ** 2) / 2
    loss.append(float(sq_loss))

Based on this information, I am going to continue by using these two variables, but I'm going to add in norm of the percentage of the population with access to work via public transportation because it seemed to be the best predictor of that split based on the graphs I made in the data visualization and exploratory analysis section.

Conclusion¶

I determined that the best model for predicting the number of high wage workers with access to work via public transportation was $$ \hat{y} = \begin{cases} p_1 & \text{if $p_1$ < 0.25}\\ p_2 & \text{if $p_1$ $\geq$ 0.25} \end{cases} $$ where $ \\ p_1 = 0.1296 + 0.2176x_1 - 0.1333x_2 \\ p_2 = 0.0645 + 0.2214x_1 - 0.1566x_2 + 0.9923x_3 $ and $ \\ x_1 = \text{the norm of the number of low wage workers with access to work via public transportation} \\ x_2 = \text{the norm of the number of medium wage workers with access to work via public transportation} \\ x_3 = \text{the norm of the percentage of the regional population able to access work via public transportation} $

I chose to use the function with only 3 predictors over the one with 5 to simplify the calculations since they both had very similar prediction results. I chose to only compare the result of only function $p_1$ to compare to the threshold to simplify calculations as well.

It makes sense that the best predictors for the number of high wage workers with access to work via public transportation would be the number of other workers with access to work via public transportation. The interesting thing about this data was that the number of high wage workers with access to public transportation split at around the 0.3 norm spot and needed a different linear equation to predict it. It was interesting that this split was only present in the high wage worker data and not the low and medium wage workers'.

I think the reason for this may be that people with more money are more able to live closer to their jobs in expensive areas rather than having to commute over a long distance, especially in expensive coastal cities that tend to have public transportation. This is just an idea and more research will need to be done to legitimize this claim.
